When you do `$(element).click(...)`, you are attaching a new listener to that element. If you do this repeatedly, those listeners will stack. In your example, each time you change the dropdown, you&#39;re adding a new event - **not** replacing the previous one.

Instead, the easiest approach might be something like this:

- Have a global variable that stores the color

- Attach a change event to your dropdown. When changed, set the global color variable to the selected option

- Attach a click event to your inputs. When clicked, set the background to the global color variable


That would look like so:



&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let backgroundColor;                                //Global var to hold color choice

    $(&quot;#change_color&quot;).on(&quot;change&quot;, function() {        //When &lt;select&gt; changes
      backgroundColor = $(this).val();                  //Update global var
    }).change();                                        //Fire this event on page-load

    $(&quot;.my-input&quot;).on(&quot;click&quot;, function() {             //When input is clicked
      $(this).toggleClass(backgroundColor);             //Toggle class
    });

